{
  "doc_id": "24843",
  "text": "Ricin is a potent inhibitor of protein synthesis that triggers a robust proinflammatory response when administered to mice and non-human primates [CITATION_1] . Mounting evidence points to the macrophage as the specific cell type responsible for ricin's lethal effects in vivo [CITATION_2] [CITATION_3] [CITATION_4] . In primary bone-marrow derived-(BMDM) and alveolar macrophages, exposure to ricin causes the phosphorylation of stress activated protein kinases (SAPKs) p38 MAPK and JNK, and triggers the transcriptional upregulation of genes encoding proinflammatory cytokines and chemokines [CITATION_5] [CITATION_6] . In vivo, depletion of macrophages prior to delivery of ricin to the pulmonary system of mice results in diminished inflammatory signs, including reduced neutrophilia and pulmonary edema [CITATION_7] .",
